  "body": "## Bug Description\n\nThe cron scheduler calculates `nextRunAtMs` based on `updatedAtMs + everyMs` instead of `lastRunAtMs + everyMs`. This causes jobs to drift forward in time whenever the job state is touched.\n\n## Impact\n\n- Jobs with `schedule.kind: \"every\"` miss scheduled runs\n- Drift accumulates: each state update pushes next run further into the future\n- Makes interval-based cron unreliable\n\n## Reproduction\n\n1. Create a job with `everyMs: 3600000` (1 hour)\n2. Let it run successfully at time T\n3. Observe `nextRunAtMs` should be T + 1hr\n4. Update the job (even just patching state)\n5. Observe `nextRunAtMs` is now `updatedAtMs + everyMs` (now + 1hr), not the original schedule\n\n## Evidence\n\n```\nJob: software-update-check (everyMs: 3600000 = 1 hour)\n\nlastRunAtMs:  1769372901882  (3:28 PM)\nExpected next: 1769376501882  (4:28 PM = lastRun + 1hr)\nActual stored: 1769381650482  (5:54 PM)\nGap: +85 minutes drift\n```\n\nAfter patching state to fix, scheduler recalculated:\n```\nnextRunAtMs = updatedAtMs + everyMs\n```\n...pushing it forward again.\n\n## Expected Behavior\n\nFor `kind: \"every\"` jobs:\n- `nextRunAtMs` should be calculated as `lastRunAtMs + everyMs`\n- State updates should NOT affect the next scheduled time\n- Only actual job execution should advance the schedule\n\n## Environment\n\n- Clawdbot version: 2026.1.24-3\n- Node: v25.4.0\n- OS: macOS Darwin 24.6.0 (arm64)\n\n## Related Issues\n\n- #1614 / #1233 (catch-up for missed runs) - related but distinct issue",
